ss-date=13 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712211144/http://foxtrotalpha.jalopnik.com/the-littoral-combat-ship-is-a-disaster-and-this-is-the-1796783565|archive-date=12 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Subclasses               = \n| Built range              = 2005\u2013present\n| In commission range      = 2008\u2013present\n| Total ships planned      = 16\n| Total ships on order     = 2\n| Total ships building     = 5\n| Total ships completed    = 9\n| Total ships cancelled    = \n| Total ships active       = 9\n| Total ships laid up      = \n| Total ships lost         = \n| Total ships retired      = \n| Total ships scrapped     = \n| Total ships preserved    = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Ship type = [[Littoral combat ship]]\n| Ship displacement = {{convert|3500|MT|ST}} (full load)<ref name=NavyLCSclass>{{cite web|title=Littoral Combat Ship Class \u2013 LCS|url=http://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/pages/LittoralCombatShips.aspx#.VTOL2vzF97E|website=America's Navy|publisher=US Navy|accessdate=19 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419135723/http://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/pages/LittoralCombatShips.aspx#.VTOL2vzF97E|archive-date=19 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Ship length = {{convert|378|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|57.4|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft = {{convert|12.8|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship power = Electrical: 4 [[Isotta Fraschini]] V1708 diesel engines, Hitzinger generator units, 800 kW each\n| Ship propulsion = 2 x [[Rolls-Royce plc|Rolls-Royce]] [[Rolls-Royce Marine Trent|MT30]] {{convert|36|MW|HP|abbr=on}} [[gas turbine]]s, 2 x [[Colt-Pielstick]] 16PA6B {{convert|6.8|MW|HP|abbr=on}} [[diesel engine]]s, 4 Rolls-Royce waterjets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fincantieri.com/en/products-and-services/naval-vessels/lcs/|title=''LCS''|publisher=Fincantieri|access-date=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227085147/https://www.fincantieri.com/en/products-and-services/naval-vessels/lcs/|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fairbanksmorse.com/colt-pielstick-pa6b-stc|title=''Colt-Pielstcik PA6B-STC''|publisher=Fairbanks Morse|access-date=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227133035/https://www.fairbanksmorse.com/colt-pielstick-pa6b-stc|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Ship speed = {{convert|47|kn}} ([[sea state]] 3)<ref name=\"navytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.navytimes.com/news/2009/05/navy_lcs_051809w/ |title=Refueling tops list of LCS crew challenges |work=NavyTimes |last=Ewing |first=Phillip |date=19 May 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n| Ship range = {{convert|3500|nmi|-2|abbr=on}} at {{convert|18|kn}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://peoships.crane.navy.mil/lcs/factsheet.htm |title=LCS Littoral Combat Ship |accessdate=20 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808165514/http://peoships.crane.navy.mil/lcs/factsheet.htm |archivedate=8 August 2007 }}</ref>\n| Ship endurance = 21 days (336 hours)\n| Ship boats = {{convert|11|m|ft|abbr=on}} RHIB, {{convert|40|ft|m|0|abbr=on}} high-speed boats\n| Ship complement = 50 core crew, 65 with mission crew (Blue and Gold crews).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140106/DEFREG02/301060023 |title=Next LCS Deployment To Last 16 Months |last1=Cavas |first1=Christopher P. |date=6 January 2014 |work=defensenews.com |publisher=Gannett Government Media Corporation |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n| Ship sensors = *[[EADS North America]] TRS-3D air and surface search radar,<ref name=\"Navtech\">{{cite web | title=Littoral Combat Ship (LCS) High-Speed Surface Ship | work=www.naval-technology.com | url=http://www.naval-technology.com/projects/littoral/ | accessdate=14 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602034747/http://www.naval-technology.com/projects/littoral | archive-date=2 June 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> TRS-4D from LCS 17<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.shephardmedia.com/news/digital-battlespace/trs-4d-radar-finishes-factory-acceptance-test/ |title=TRS-4D radar finishes factory acceptance test |date=14 November 2016 |website=www.shephardmedia.com |publisher=The Shephard News |accessdate=14 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114232433/https://www.shephardmedia.com/news/digital-battlespace/trs-4d-radar-finishes-factory-acceptance-test/ |archive-date=14 November 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Lockheed Martin]] COMBATSS-21 combat management system<ref name=\"Navtech\"/>\n*AN/SQR-20 Multi-Function Towed Array (As part of ASW mission module)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deagel.com/Ship-Sensors/ANSQR-20_a002184001.aspx |title=AN/SQR-20 |publisher=deagel.com |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812033433/http://www.deagel.com/Ship-Sensors/ANSQR-20_a002184001.aspx |archive-date=12 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://www.foils.org/01_Mtg_Presdnloads/LCS_SNAME_IHS041023.pdf Littoral Combat Ship at the Joint Meeting INTERNATIONAL HYDROFOIL SOCIETY SNAME Panel SD-5]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308211250/http://www.foils.org/01_Mtg_Presdnloads/LCS_SNAME_IHS041023.pdf |date=8 March 2012 }}</ref>\n| Ship EW = *[[Argon ST]] WBR-2000 [[Electronic Support Measures|ESM system]]\n*[[Terma A/S]] SKWS decoy system<ref name=\"Navtech\"/>\n| Ship armament = *1 \u00d7 [[BAE Systems Land and Armaments|BAE Systems]] [[Mk 110 57 mm gun]], 400 rounds in turret and two ready service magazines with 240 rounds each.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navsea.navy.mil/nswc/dahlgren/ET/LCS/default.aspx |title=Littoral Combat Ship |publisher=Navsea \u2013 NSWC Dahlgren Division |accessdate=14 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613080400/http://www.navsea.navy.mil/nswc/dahlgren/ET/LCS/default.aspx |archivedate=13 June 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*1 x [[List of United States Navy Guided Missile Launching Systems|Mk 49 launcher]] with 21 \u00d7 [[RIM-116 Rolling Airframe Missile|RIM-116 Rolling Airframe]] [[Surface-to-Air Missile]]s\n*4 \u00d7 .50 in (12.7 mm) machine guns\n*2 \u00d7 30 mm [[Mk44 Bushmaster II]] guns (part of SUW module)\n*24 \u00d7 [[AGM-114 Hellfire|AGM-114L Hellfire]] missiles (planned part of SUW module)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1900 |title=Q & A with the U.S. Navy on Lockheed Martin Hellfire missiles for Littoral Combat Ships |work=navyrecognition.com |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727232007/http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1900 |archive-date=27 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Other weapons as part of mission-specific modules\n| Ship aircraft = *1 \u00d7 [[SH-60 Seahawk|MH-60R/S Seahawk]]\n*2 \u00d7 [[MQ-8B Fire Scout]]s or 1 \u00d7 [[Northrop Grumman MQ-8C Fire Scout|MQ-8C Fire Scout]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2014/12/fire-scout-grows-up-drone-getting-radar-rockets-2016-ioc/ |title=Fire Scout Grows Up: Drone Getting Radar, Rockets, 2016 IOC |last=Freedburg Jr. |first=Sydney J. |work=Breakingdefense.com |date=17 December 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627150719/http://breakingdefense.com/2014/12/fire-scout-grows-up-drone-getting-radar-rockets-2016-ioc/ |archive-date=27 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| Ship aircraft facilities = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''''Freedom'' class''' is one of two [[ship class|classes]] of the [[littoral combat ship]] program, built for the [[United States Navy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/fact_display.asp?cid=4200&tid=1650&ct=4|title=US Navy Fact File: LITTORAL COMBAT SHIP CLASS \u2013 LCS|publisher=United States Department of the Navy|accessdate=14 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302070526/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/fact_display.asp?cid=4200&tid=1650&ct=4|archive-date=2 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Freedom'' class was proposed by a consortium formed by [[Lockheed Martin]] as \"prime contractor\" and by [[Fincantieri]] (project) through the subsidiary [[Marinette Marine]] (manufacturer) as a contender for a fleet of small, multipurpose warships to operate in the [[littoral zone]]. Two ships were approved, to compete with the {{sclass-|Independence|littoral combat ship|0}} design offered by [[General Dynamics]] and [[Austal]] for a construction contract of up to 55 vessels.\n\nDespite initial plans to only accept two of the ''Freedom'' and ''Independence'' variants,{{clarify|two total or two of each?|date=May 2018}} the U.S. Navy has since announced plans to order up to ten additional ships of each class, for a total twelve ships per class.<ref name=\"NNS101229-09\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=57917 |title=Littoral Combat Ship Contract Award Announced |author=Special from Navy Office of Information |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |number=NNS101229-09 |date=29 December 2010 |accessdate=30 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925220022/http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=57917 |archive-date=25 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>  {{As of|2016}}, five ships are active and an additional nine are either on order, under construction or fitting out.\n\nIt was announced in early September 2016 that the first four vessels of the LCS program would be used as test ships rather than being deployed with the fleet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacewar.com/reports/US_Navy_announces_Littoral_Combat_Ship_program_overhaul_999.html|title=U.S. Navy announces Littoral Combat Ship program overhaul|access-date=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916041024/http://www.spacewar.com/reports/US_Navy_announces_Littoral_Combat_Ship_program_overhaul_999.html|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/09/12/politics/us-navy-littoral-combat-ship-overhaul/index.html|title=US Navy overhauls troubled littoral combat ship program|author=Brad Lendon and Ryan Browne|website=CNN|access-date=13 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827085236/http://www.cnn.com/2016/09/12/politics/us-navy-littoral-combat-ship-overhaul/index.html|archive-date=27 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>  This includes ''Freedom'' and ''Fort Worth''. In February 2020 it was announced that the Navy plans to retire the first four LCS ships.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/navy-ships/a30878764/littoral-combat-ship-retirement/|title=The Navy Wants to Retire a Ship That's Only Six Years Old|author=Kyle Mizokami|publisher=Popular Mechanics|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Planning and construction==\n[[File:USS-Freedom-rear-130222-N-DR144-367.jpg|thumb|left|''Freedom'' in February 2013 showing her large helideck and a [[RIM-116 Rolling Airframe Missile|RAM]] launcher on the hangar.]]\n\nPlanning for a class of small, multipurpose warships to operate in the littoral zone began in the early 2000s. The construction contract was awarded to Lockheed Martin's LCS team (Lockheed Martin, [[Gibbs & Cox]], [[Marinette Marine]], [[Bollinger Shipyards]]) in May 2004 for two vessels. These would then be compared to two ships built by Austal USA to determine which design would be taken up by the Navy for a production run of up to 55 ships.\n\nOn 15 April 2003, the Lockheed Martin LCS team unveiled their Sea Blade concept based on the hull form of the motor yacht ''[[Destriero]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ross |first=Ken |url=http://www.lockheedmartin.com/news/press_releases/2003/LockheedMartinLCSTeamIntroducesSeaB.html |title=Lockheed Martin LCS Team Introduces Sea Blade Concept for Navy's LCS Program |publisher=[[Lockheed Martin]] |date=15 April 2003}} {{dead link|date=March 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lockheedmartin.com/data/assets/ms2/pdf/LCS_Trifold_Brochure.pdf \"LCS Brochure\"]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100705072832/http://www.lockheedmartin.com/data/assets/ms2/pdf/LCS_Trifold_Brochure.pdf |date=5 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe keel of the lead ship {{USS|Freedom|LCS-1|2}} was laid down in June 2005, by Marinette Marine in [[Marinette, Wisconsin]].<ref name=Onley>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcn.com/online/vol1_no1/31385-1.html|first=Dawn|last=Onley|title=Lockheed Martin to build advanced Navy ship|publisher=Government Computer News |accessdate=23 September 2006|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070304113539/http://www.gcn.com/online/vol1_no1/31385-1.html |archivedate=4 March 2007}}</ref> She was christened in September 2006,<ref name=NavyNews>{{cite press release |url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=25737 |title=First Littoral Combat Ship Christened |author=Chief of Naval Operations Public Affairs |id=NNS060924-01 |publisher=Navy News Service |date=24 September 2006 |accessdate=10 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222155437/http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=25737 |archive-date=22 December 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Lockheed Martin Team Delivers Nation's First Littoral Combat Ship to U.S. Navy |url= http://biz.yahoo.com/prnews/080918/neth118.html?.v=2 |archive-url= https://archive.today/20120701183227/http://biz.yahoo.com/prnews/080918/neth118.html?.v=2 |url-status= dead |archive-date= 1 July 2012 |accessdate= 20 September 2008}}</ref> delivered to the Navy in September 2008, and commissioned that November.<ref name=\"navy40822\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=40822 |title=USS Freedom Commissioned in Milwaukee |author=Chief Mass Communication Specialist Rhonda Burke |id=NNS081108-20 |publisher=Navy News Service |date=8 November 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629152229/http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=40822 |archive-date=29 June 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> During [[INSURV]] trials, 2,600 discrepancies were discovered, including 21 considered high-priority.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ewing |first=Philip |url=http://www.navytimes.com/news/2009/12/navy_lcs2_acceptance_120909w/ |title=Navy: InSurv recommends accepting LCS 2 |work=[[Military Times]] |date=9 December 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Not all of these were rectified before the ship entered service, as moving the ship away from [[Milwaukee]] before the winter freeze was considered a higher priority.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d09326sp.pdf |id=GAO-09-326SP |title=Assessments of Selected Weapon Programs |publisher=United States Government Accountability Office |date=March 2009 |pages=106 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206115911/http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d09326sp.pdf |archive-date=6 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCost overruns during ''Freedom''{{'}}s construction combined with projected future overruns led the government to issue a \"Stop-work\" in January 2007 and ultimately led to the cancellation of construction of LCS-3 (the second Lockheed Martin ship) on 13 April 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/cost-growth-leads-to-stopwork-on-team-lockheed-lcs3-construction-updated-02957?ref=/ |title=Cost Growth Leads To Stop-Work On Team Lockheed LCS-3 Construction |work=Defense Industry Daily |date=16 April 2007 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402233127/http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/cost-growth-leads-to-stopwork-on-team-lockheed-lcs3-construction-updated-02957/?ref=%2F |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> This ship was later re-ordered.\n\nAfter much inconsistency on how testing and orders were to proceed, in November 2010, the Navy asked that Congress approve ten of both the ''Freedom'' and ''Independence'' variants.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sessions |first=Jeff |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/news/2010/11/mil-101103-sessions01.htm |title=Sessions comments today regarding the Navy's proposal to purchase additional Littoral Combat Ship |publisher=Office of Jeff Sessions |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111014145009/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/news/2010/11/mil-101103-sessions01.htm |archive-date=14 October 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2010/11/03/navy-ships-idUSWEN247520101103 |title=US Navy said to buy LCS warships from both bidders |work=[[Reuters]] |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402125550/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2010/11/03/navy-ships-idUSWEN247520101103 |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cavas |first=Christopher P. |url=http://www.navytimes.com/news/2010/11/defense-navy-picks-both-lcs-designs-110310/ |title=Navy asks Congress to buy both LCS designs |work=NavyTimes |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:US Navy 090928-N-7241L-232 The littoral combat ship USS Freedom (LCS 1) conducts flight deck certification with an MH-60S Sea Hawk helicopter assigned to the Sea Knights of Helicopter Sea Combat Squadron (HSC) 22.jpg|thumb|An MH-60 Seahawk helicopter approaching ''Freedom'' in 2009]]\n\nThe ship is a [[Wave making resistance#Semi-displacement and planing hulls|semi-planing]] steel monohull with an aluminum [[superstructure]]. It is {{convert|377|ft|m|0}} in length, displaces {{convert|3,500|metric ton}}, and can achieve {{convert|47|kn|lk=in}}. The design incorporates a large reconfigurable seaframe to allow rapidly interchangeable mission modules, a [[flight deck]] with integrated helicopter launch, recovery and handling system and the capability to launch and recover boats (manned and unmanned) from both the stern and side.\n\nThe flight deck is one and a half times larger than that of a standard surface ship{{clarify|date=February 2018}}, and uses a Trigon traversing system to move helicopters in and out of the hangar. The ship has two ways to launch and recover various mission packages: a stern ramp and a starboard side door near the waterline. The mission module bay has a 3-axis crane for positioning modules or cargo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lockheedmartin.com/news/press_releases/2007/101107_LCSDEMONSTRATESKEYMISSIONPACKAGE.html |title=Nation\u2019s First Littoral Combat Ship Demonstrates Key Mission Package Launch And Recovery System |publisher=Lockheed Martin |date=11 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820050859/http://www.lockheedmartin.com/news/press_releases/2007/101107_LCSDEMONSTRATESKEYMISSIONPACKAGE.html |archivedate=20 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe most serious problems with the ''Freedom'' class are with the electrical systems.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2014/01/littoral-combat-ship-cut-plan-reopens-navy-riff-build-em-fast-or-rugged/ |title=Littoral Combat Ship Cut Plan Reopens Navy Riff: Build \u2018Em Fast Or Rugged |work=Breakingdefense.com |last=Freedberg Jr. |first=Sydney J. |date=17 January 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320192144/http://breakingdefense.com/2014/01/littoral-combat-ship-cut-plan-reopens-navy-riff-build-em-fast-or-rugged/ |archive-date=20 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{clarify|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe fore deck has a modular weapons zone which can be used for a [[Bofors 57 mm L/70 naval artillery gun|57&nbsp;mm gun turret]] or missile launcher. A [[Rolling Airframe Missile]] launcher is mounted above the hangar for short-range defense against aircraft and [[cruise missile]]s, and .50-caliber gun mounts are provided topside. The {{sclass2-|Fleet|unmanned surface vessel|2}} is designed for operations from ''Freedom'' variant ships.<ref name=\"Flight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/auvsi-making-a-splash-346474/|title=AUVSI: Making a splash|last=Sobie|first=Brendan|date=24 August 2010|work=Flightglobal|publisher=Reed Business Information|accessdate=14 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101030321/http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/auvsi-making-a-splash-346474/|archive-date=1 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe core crew will be 40 sailors, usually joined by a mission package crew and an aviation detachment for a total crew of about 75. Automation allows a reduced crew, which greatly reduces operating costs, but workload can still be \"gruelling\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/archive/2010/September/Pages/DutyAboardtheLittoralCombatShip%E2%80%98GruelingbutManageable%E2%80%99.aspx |accessdate=14 March 2015 |title=Duty Aboard the Littoral Combat Ship: \u2018Grueling but Manageable\u2019 |date=September 2010 |last=Jean |first=Grace V. |work=National Defense |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305060530/http://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/archive/2010/September/Pages/DutyAboardtheLittoralCombatShip%E2%80%98GruelingbutManageable%E2%80%99.aspx |archivedate=5 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> During testing of the [[lead ship|class lead]], two [[Ship's company|ship's companies]] will rotate on four-month assignments.<ref name=\"mjones\">{{cite news |url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/milwaukee/33947284.html |last=Jones |first=Meg |title=Navy's Vessel Of Versatility |work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] |date=5 November 2008 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108095409/http://www.jsonline.com/news/milwaukee/33947284.html |archive-date=8 January 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFour 750-kilowatt Fincantieri [[Isotta Fraschini]] diesel generators provide 3 megawatts of electrical power to power the ship systems.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mae.pennnet.com/display_article/325943/32/ARTCL/none/none/1/USS-Freedom-demonstrates-its-power-plant-can-handle-vessel\u2019s-sensors-and-electronics/ |title=USS ''Freedom'' demonstrates its power plant can handle vessel\u2019s sensors and electronics |last=Howard |first=Courtenay E. |work=Military & Aerospace Electronics |date=1 April 2008 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Congressional Budget Office]] estimates that fuel will account for only \"8 percent to 18 percent\" of the total life-cycle costs for ''Freedom''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbo.gov/publication/21398 |title=Life-Cycle Costs of Selected Navy Ships |publisher=Congressional Budget Office |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402101948/https://www.cbo.gov/publication/21398 |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Senator [[Jeff Sessions]] of Alabama has called the report into question and has suggested that ''Independence'', built in his state, would be more fuel efficient and that less frequent refuelings would affect military operations beyond the cost of fuel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bignews.biz/?id=866364&keys=Senator-Jeff-Sessions-NavalVessels |title=CBO Report Calls into Question Navy\u2019s LCS Evaluation |work=Bignews.biz |date=29 April 2010 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402104104/http://bignews.biz/?id=866364&keys=Senator-Jeff-Sessions-NavalVessels |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, a Navy cybersecurity team found major deficiencies in Lockheed's Total Ship Computing Environment, which controls the entire ship in order to reduce crewing requirements.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-23/littoral-combat-ship-network-can-be-hacked-navy-finds.html |title=Littoral Combat Ship Network Can Be Hacked, Navy Finds |last1=Capaccio |first1=Tony |date=23 April 2013 |work=Bloomberg News |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126012210/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-23/littoral-combat-ship-network-can-be-hacked-navy-finds.html |archive-date=26 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afcea.org/content/?q=node/1055 |title=Littoral Combat Ship Launches Change |last1=Lawlor |first1=Maryann |date=December 2005 |work=SIGNAL Online |publisher=AFCEA International |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402170740/http://www.afcea.org/content/?q=node%2F1055 |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSurvivability has been a criticism of both Littoral Combat Ship classes, rated at level one by the Navy, compared to level two for the {{sclass-|Oliver Hazard Perry|frigate|0}} [[guided-missile frigate]]s (FFG) they were designed to replace. Lockheed claims the ''Freedom'' class is actually more survivable than the FFGs because Navy requirements for various survivability levels have changed since the FFGs were assessed, and because the ''Freedom''s{{'}} hull is made of high-strength, low-weight steel that was not previously available.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2014/06/lockheed-says-it-can-easily-improve-lcs/ |title=Lockheed Says It Can \u2018Easily\u2019 Improve LCS |work=Breakingdefense.com |last=Freedberg Jr. |first=Sydney J. |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327042646/http://breakingdefense.com/2014/06/lockheed-says-it-can-easily-improve-lcs/ |archive-date=27 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{USS|Milwaukee|LCS-5|2}} was the first ''Freedom''-class LCS to be fitted with [[cavitation]] performance waterjets (Rolls Royce Axial-Flow Waterjet Mk-1<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newatlas.com/lcs-water-jets/26114/ |title=New water jets to give U.S. Navy littoral combat ships extra punch |work=Newatlas.com |last=Szondy |first=David |date=6 Feb 2013 |accessdate=6 Feb 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207010141/https://newatlas.com/lcs-water-jets/26114/ |archive-date=7 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>). The jets create partial vacuums in liquid using an improved impeller blade design. Cavitation jets do not increase the ship's top speed, but deliver 10 percent greater fuel efficiency with less noise and vibration, reduced life-cycle costs, improved maintainability, increased availability, and potentially improved efficiency at lower speeds. The Navy plans to add the new waterjets to every ''Freedom'' variant that is produced, including LCS 5, 7, 9, 11, and 13.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://defensetech.org/2014/05/15/lcs5-gets-new-waterjets/ |title=LCS5 Gets New Waterjets |work=Defensetech.org |last=Osborn |first=Kris |date=15 May 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094443/http://defensetech.org/2014/05/15/lcs5-gets-new-waterjets/ |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The mixed flow design was changed to an axial design to push water parallel to the shaft of the impeller.<ref name=\"dodbuzz27june14\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/06/27/navy-engineers-lcs-changes/ |title=Navy Engineers LCS Changes |work=DoDBuzz.com |last=Osborn |first=Kris |date=27 June 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150429110622/http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/06/27/navy-engineers-lcs-changes/ |archive-date=29 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe first ships of both LCS classes were delivered before the designs were mature so that improvements could be built into future ships. Many improvements to the ''Freedom'' class came from the problems experienced by ''Freedom'' (LCS-1) on its first deployment including power outages, corroded equipment, and a faulty air compressor. To prevent water being taken into the anchor windlass room, the anchor winch, hydraulic unit, and mooring capstan were replaced with a single electric chain winch on the main deck, and the existing towing chain was replaced with a lighter chain. Corrosion resistance was also improved by the Impressed Current Cathodic Protection system being modified by adding protections to the water jet inlet tunnel. Starting with LCS-3, the stern transom was lengthened and buoyancy tanks were added to the stern to increase weight service and enhance stability. A significantly less complex gas turbine electric start system will be added on LCS-5 to reduce costs and lower ship weight.<ref name=\"dodbuzz27june14\"/>\n\nStarting with LCS-17, the ''Freedom''-class ships will be equipped with the TRS-4D naval radar.  The TRS-4D is an [[AESA radar]] built by [[Airbus Defense and Space]] that is similar to the one on German {{sclass2-|F125|frigate|1}}s, the difference being the LCS will have a rotating version instead of a fixed panel, the first AESA rotating radar aboard a U.S. Navy ship. It is a three-dimensional, multi-function naval radar combining mechanical and electronic azimuth scanning that delivers increased sensitivity to detect smaller targets with greater accuracy and faster track generation.<ref>[http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3299 Successful Factory Acceptance for US Navy Freedom class LCS' TRS-4D AESA Radar] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124175219/http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3299 |date=24 January 2016 }} \u2013 Navyrecognition.com, 2 December 2015</ref>\n\n===Engine maintenance incidents===\n{{As of|2016|11}}, three of four active ''Freedom''-class littoral combat ships have suffered engine maintenance incidents. ''Milwaukee'' broke down in the Atlantic Ocean in December 2015 and had to be towed back to port. Metallic debris was found in the filter system. The cause was traced to a clutch between the gas turbine and diesel engine systems, which failed to disengage as designed while switching from one propulsion system to the other. ''Fort Worth'' suffered a similar breakdown in the Pacific Ocean in January 2016. Improper procedures used aboard ship caused a set of combining gears\u2014hardware used to transfer power to the ship's water propulsion system\u2014to be operated with insufficient oil. And in July 2016, ''Freedom'' suffered a seawater leak into one of its two main diesel propulsion systems and had to return to San Diego for seawater decontamination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/29/politics/us-navy-littoral-combat-ship-breakdowns/index.html|title=Third breakdown in year for $360M US Navy warships|author=Brad Lendon and Zachary Cohen|website=CNN|access-date=30 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830034333/http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/29/politics/us-navy-littoral-combat-ship-breakdowns/index.html|archive-date=30 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Ships==\nSeven ''Freedom''-class LCS ships have been commissioned, two more ships are being fitted out, four more are under construction and three are on order.\n\n===Ship orders and naming history===\nThe Navy originally ordered two ''Freedom''-class littoral combat ships, the lead ship ''Freedom'' (LCS-1) and {{USS|Fort Worth|LCS-3|3}}, announced in March 2009 by then-[[Secretary of the Navy]] [[Donald C. Winter]], with even hull numbers being used for the ''Independence'' class. On 29 December 2010, the Navy announced that it would be placing a block-buy order of up to ten additional ''Freedom''-class ships, for a total of 12 ships in the class.<ref name=\"NNS101229-09\" /> On 31 March 2016, the Navy exercised an option under the block-buy contract for one additional ''Freedom''-class vessel; LCS-25 would be the eleventh vessel built under the block-buy contract and the thirteenth overall (''Freedom'' and ''Fort Worth'' were built prior to the block-buy order).<ref name=\"LM PR LCS25 Order\" />\n\nOn 10 March 2014, the Navy awarded contract options to fund construction of LCS-17 and LCS-19, the seventh and eighth ships in a 10-ship contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lockheedmartin.com/us/news/features/2014/140310-mst-on-your-mark-get-set-go-lcs-17-19-at-the-starting-line.html |title=On Your Mark\u2026 Get Set\u2026 Go! LCS 17, 19 at the Starting Line |publisher=Lockheed Martin |date=10 March 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320152137/http://lockheedmartin.com/us/news/features/2014/140310-mst-on-your-mark-get-set-go-lcs-17-19-at-the-starting-line.html |archive-date=20 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 April 2015 the Navy awarded LCS-21 to Lockheed Martin.<ref>{{cite news |first=Grace |last=Jean |title=USN awards FY 2015 LCS contracts |url=http://www.janes.com/article/50397/usn-awards-fy-2015-lcs-contracts |date=1 April 2015 |publisher=IHS Jane's Navy International |accessdate=11 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702102643/http://www.janes.com/article/50397/usn-awards-fy-2015-lcs-contracts |archive-date=2 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 April 2016, the Navy awarded a contract to Lockheed Martin for LCS-25, the thirteenth of the ''Freedom''-class variants.<ref name=\"LM PR LCS25 Order\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lockheedmartin.com/us/news/press-releases/2016/april/160401-mst-lockheed-martin-led-team-awarded-contract-to-build-lcs-25.html|title=Navy awards contract for LCS-25|accessdate=4 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406095004/http://www.lockheedmartin.com/us/news/press-releases/2016/april/160401-mst-lockheed-martin-led-team-awarded-contract-to-build-lcs-25.html|archive-date=6 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 October 2017, Marinette Marine announced the order to build LCS-27, at a cost under the congressional cost cap of $584 million.<ref name=\"Austal PR LCS30 Order\">{{cite press release |url=http://fincantierimarinegroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/LCS-27-Contract-Award-News-Release.pdf |title=Lockheed Martin and Fincantieri Marinette Marine Awarded Contract to Build LCS 27 |publisher=Marinette Marine |date=9 October 2017 |access-date=9 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010010812/http://fincantierimarinegroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/LCS-27-Contract-Award-News-Release.pdf |archive-date=10 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February 2018, Navy Secretary [[Richard V. Spencer]] announced the name of LCS-27 as ''Nantucket''.<ref name=\"lcs name\">{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=104365|title=Secretary of the Navy Names Two Littoral Combat Ships|publisher=navy.mil|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=14 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214022206/http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=104365|archive-date=14 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September 2018, the Navy announced that two additional ''Independence''-class ships, and one ''Freedom''-class ship, have been ordered.<ref name=\"New LCS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=107121|title=Navy Awards Three Littoral Combat Ships|publisher=navy.mil|date=18 September 2018|accessdate=19 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919034157/https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=107121|archive-date=19 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 January 2019, the Navy exercised an option in their contract with Lockheed Martin to purchase a single ''Freedom''-class variant, which will be numbered LCS-31.<ref name=\"LCS31a\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.navsea.navy.mil/Media/News/SavedNewsModule/Article/1732665/navy-statement-on-littoral-combat-ship|title=Navy Statement on Littoral Combat Ship|publisher=NAVSEA|date=15 January 2019|access-date=5 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120043125/https://www.navsea.navy.mil/Media/News/SavedNewsModule/Article/1732665/navy-statement-on-littoral-combat-ship/|archive-date=20 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Ships in class===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ship\n! Hull Number\n! Laid down\n! Launched\n! Commissioned\n! Status\n|-\n|{{USS|Freedom|LCS-1|2}}\n|LCS-1\n|2 June 2005\n|23 September 2006\n|8 November 2008\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|Fort Worth|LCS-3|2}}\n|LCS-3\n|11 July 2009\n|7 December 2010\n|22 September 2012\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|Milwaukee|LCS-5|2}}\n|LCS-5\n|27 October 2011\n|18 December 2013\n|21 November 2015\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|Detroit|LCS-7|2}}\n|LCS-7\n|11 August 2012\n|18 October 2014\n|22 October 2016\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|Little Rock|LCS-9|2}}\n|LCS-9\n|27 June 2013\n|18 July 2015\n|16 December 2017\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|Sioux City|LCS-11|2}}\n|LCS-11\n|19 February 2014\n|30 January 2016\n|17 November 2018\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|Wichita|LCS-13|2}}\n|LCS-13\n|9 February 2015\n|17 September 2016\n|12 January 2019\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|Billings|LCS-15|2}}\n|LCS-15\n|2 November 2015\n|1 July 2017\n|3 August 2019\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|Indianapolis|LCS-17|2}}\n|LCS-17\n|18 July 2016\n|18 April 2018\n|26 October 2019\n|Active in service\n|-\n|{{USS|St. Louis|LCS-19|2}}\n|LCS-19\n|17 May 2017\n|15 December 2018\n|\n|Fitting out\n|-\n|{{USS|Minneapolis-Saint Paul |LCS-21|2}}\n|LCS-21\n|22 February 2018\n|15 June 2019\n|\n|Fitting out\n|-\n|{{USS|Cooperstown|LCS-23|2}}\n|LCS-23\n|14 August 2018\n|19 January 2020\n|\n|Fitting out\n|-\n|{{USS|Marinette|LCS-25|2}}\n|LCS-25\n|27 March 2019\n|\n|\n|Under construction\n|-\n|{{USS|Nantucket|LCS-27|2}}\n|LCS-27\n|9 October 2019\n|\n|\n|Under construction\n|-\n|{{USS|Beloit|LCS-29|2}}\n|LCS-29\n|\n|\n|\n|Under construction\n|-\n|{{USS|Cleveland|LCS-31|2}}\n|LCS-31\n|\n|\n|\n|On order<ref name=\"LCS31a\"/>\n|-<!----\n|\n|LCS-33\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n|LCS-35\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n|LCS-37\n|\n|\n|\n|---->\n|}\n*<small>Note: The Navy has placed orders for ''Independence''-class variants numbered LCS-32, LCS-34, LCS-36 & LCS-38, but as of September 2018, have not as of yet placed orders for additional ''Freedom''-class variants, that would become LCS-33, LCS-35, & LCS-37 in the dual-class numbering scheme.</small>\n\n====Plan to scrap LCS hulls 1-4====\nDuring planning for the [[United States federal budget|FY21 Budget]] [[Military budget of the United States|proposal]], Navy recommended the scrapping of hulls 1-4 in 2021, some 10 years ahead of prior planning.<ref name=\u201d2019-12-24_NT\u201d>[https://www.navytimes.com/naval/2019/12/24/us-navy-proposes-decommissioning-first-4-lcs-more-than-a-decade-early/ US Navy proposes decommissioning first 4 LCS more than a decade early],  David B. Larter, [[Navy Times]], 2019-12-24</ref> This was explained by [[Chief of Naval Operations]], Admiral [[Mike Gilday]], during the [[WEST Conference]] on 2 March 2020, when he said, \"We made a decision a number of years ago. \u2026 In order to give capability to LCS 5 and beyond, particularly the block buys we did in 2015, we decided we needed to do much more testing and use those first four hulls, so that we could better understand what were the issues with respect to hull maintenance and engineering that kept plaguing us and kept us from getting those ships to sea. \u2026 We used those first hulls to test and we put no money into upgrading them like the rest of the fleet. \u2026 Those first four ships are not bringing lethality to the fight. \u2026 I just didn\u2019t see the return on investment.\u201d There was also a comment that it would cost another $2 billion to get the first four hulls prepped for sea duty.<ref name=\u201d2020-03-03_NT\u201d>[https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2020/03/03/cno-sounds-off-with-all-due-respect-about-how-the-navy-trains-and-deploys-crews/ CNO sounds off \u2018with all due respect\u2019 about how the Navy trains and deploys crews], Geoff Ziezulewicz], [[Navy Times]], 2020-03-03</ref>\n\n==''Freedom''-class based variants==\n===Small Surface Combatant variant===\nLockheed submitted a variety of upgrade options for ''Freedom''-class ships to the Small Surface Combatant Task Force, aimed at transforming the Littoral Combat Ship from \"niche\" platforms into ships with more protection and firepower beyond Flight 0 to survive against more advanced military adversaries.  With 180 metric tons of space available for mission packages, there is room for added capabilities.  Anti-aircraft warfare was suggested with the installation of a [[Aegis Combat System|SPY-1F air defense radar]] and permanently installed vertical launch systems (VLS). Current 118-meter length versions could house 4 to 32 VLS cells, each holding four [[Evolved Sea Sparrow|RIM-162D Evolved Sea Sparrow Missiles]] or one [[RIM-66 Standard|SM-2 missile]]. For surface warfare, the 57mm gun could be replaced with a larger weapon up to the [[5\"/54 caliber Mark 45 gun|Mk 45 5-inch]]; integration of the [[AGM-114 Hellfire|AGM-114L Hellfire missile]] for defense against fast attack craft (FAC) was also factored in.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.usni.org/2014/06/10/8077 |title=Lockheed Outlines Post Littoral Combat Ship Pitch |publisher=U.S. Naval Institute |last=LeGrone |first=Sam |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222172101/http://news.usni.org/2014/06/10/8077 |archive-date=22 December 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lockheed's approach was to integrate mission systems into the hull so that the ships could perform anti-submarine, anti-surface, and anti-aircraft duties without needing to swap out mission packages. Weight would be increased from 3,400 tons to 3,600 tons and the hull could be stretched an additional {{convert|7|-|10|m|ft|abbr=on}}. In addition to adding vertical launch tubes and a sonar, the main gun would be integrated with the stronger and more sophisticated radar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://defensetech.org/2014/09/03/lockheed-offers-navy-new-lcs-variant/ |title=Lockheed Offers Navy New LCS Variant |work=Defensetech.org |last=Osborn |first=Kris |date=3 September 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326110930/http://defensetech.org/2014/09/03/lockheed-offers-navy-new-lcs-variant/ |archive-date=26 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Navy's recommendation to base the Small Surface Combatant on upgraded versions of both ''Freedom'' and ''Independence'' LCSs was accepted in December 2014. Although Lockheed submitted improvements including vertical launch systems, 76&nbsp;mm guns, and advanced combat systems and sensors, the Navy opted to keep the 57&nbsp;mm gun, not add a vertical launch system, and chose to add an upgraded 3-D radar. Other changes included installation of an unspecified over-the-horizon missile, [[M242 Bushmaster|Mark 38 25 mm guns]], a torpedo countermeasures system, a multifunction towed array system, installation of the [[SeaRAM]] launcher, an upgraded countermeasures decoy system, an upgraded [[electronic warfare]] system, armor added to vital spaces, and improved signature management.  The SSC will focus in SUW and ASW with these additions, as well as retaining all other features of their mission packages; the SSC is not required to perform MCM, which will continue to be handled by the LCS.  The vessels will retain a degree of modularity to concentrate on one mission set and will still have mission bays, although they may be reduced. SSC vessels are planned to begin procurement by 2019, and it is being investigated if the enhancements can be added to existing LCS hulls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20141211/DEFREG02/312110041/Hagel-New-Ship-Based-LCS |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141214154956/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20141211/DEFREG02/312110041/Hagel-New-Ship-Based-LCS |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 December 2014 |title=Split Decision on New US Navy Ship |last=Cavas |first=Christopher P. |work=Defensenews.com |date=11 December 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== Multi-Mission Combat Ship variant ===\nIn 2012, Lockheed renamed the Surface Combat Ship (SCS) to match GD's Multi-Mission Combatant term and revealed that the full capabilities, such as Aegis, would only be available on a stretched 3,500 ton hull.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Blenkey |title=Lockheed Martin Offers LCS-derived Multi-Mission Combatant |url=https://www.marinelog.com/news/lockheed-martin-offers-lcs-derived-multi-mission-combatant/ |date=10 December 2012 |publisher=Marine Log |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121210054930/http://www.marinelog.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3108%3A2012-10-23-10-15-15&catid=1%3Alatest-news&Itemid=195 |archive-date=10 December 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLockheed has also been working on a trimmed down version of the ''Freedom''-class LCS to offer on the international market for smaller patrol vessels.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wall |first=Robert |date=26 October 2012 |title=BAE and Thales plot course for smaller warships to fight pirates |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/bae-and-thales-plot-course-for-smaller-warships-to-fight-pirates-8227549.html |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714215352/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/bae-and-thales-plot-course-for-smaller-warships-to-fight-pirates-8227549.html |archive-date=14 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> This Multi-Mission Combat Ship adds in phased-array radar and a vertical launch system on a smaller hull with a smaller crew size, at the cost of removing the high speed gas turbines and one third of the mission module area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20130217/DEFREG04/302170014/China-Shipbuilder-Calls-Greater-Cooperation-U-S-Firms |title=China Shipbuilder Calls for Greater Cooperation with U.S. Firms |last=Cavas |first=Christopher P. |work=DefenseNews |date=17 February 2013 |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nA much larger more capable frigate design was submitted to meet the requirements of the U.S. Navy's proposed [[FFG(X)]] program. Although based on the ''Freedom'' hull form, it has to be bigger and more heavily armed to meet more demanding mission requirements. In February 2018, this design was one of the five finalists selected to be considered for the 20-ship contract which will be awarded in 2020.\n\n==Foreign sales==\n===Saudi Arabia===\nLockheed Martin has offered an [[Aegis Combat System]]-equipped variant for [[national missile defense]] [[radar picket]] use to a number of [[Arab states of the Persian Gulf|Persian Gulf states]].<ref name=\"USNI 11.25B Deal\">{{cite web |url=http://news.usni.org/2015/10/20/saudi-arabia-set-to-buy-four-lockheed-martin-freedom-class-variants-in-11-25b-deal |title=Saudi Arabia Set to Buy Four Lockheed Martin Freedom-Class Variants in $11.25B Deal |last=LeGrone |first=Sam |publisher=U.S. Naval Institute |date=20 October 2015 |accessdate=10 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222091634/http://news.usni.org/2015/10/20/saudi-arabia-set-to-buy-four-lockheed-martin-freedom-class-variants-in-11-25b-deal |archive-date=22 December 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"DN 11.25B Deal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story/breaking-news/2015/10/20/us-oks-potential-1125b-saudi-deal-lcs-variant/74280014/ |title=US OKs Potential $11.25B Saudi Deal for LCS Variant |last=Cavas |first=Christopher P. |publisher=Defensenews.com |date=20 October 2015 |accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Surface Combat Ship was offered to Saudi Arabia as part of a 2011 arms deal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wolf |first=Jim |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/08/us-saudi-usa-arms-idUSTRE73787G20110408 |title=Saudis ask U.S. for price quotes for warships |work=Reuters |date=8 April 2011 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222170511/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/08/us-saudi-usa-arms-idUSTRE73787G20110408 |archive-date=22 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://www.lockheedmartin.com/ms2/features/SCS_euronaval_102710.html \"Surface Combat Ship Designed as a Multi-mission Ship.\"] {{dead link|date=March 2015}}</ref> The total cost for the eight ships was reported to be as much as $5 billion.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/lockheed-proposes-5bn-aegis-ships-sale-saudi-arabia-402233.html |title=Lockheed proposes $5bn Aegis ships sale to Saudi Arabia |work=Arabian Business.com |agency=Bloomberg News |date=26 May 2011 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318183034/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/lockheed-proposes-5bn-aegis-ships-sale-saudi-arabia-402233.html |archive-date=18 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Saudi Naval Expansion Program II calls for some $20 billion for new warships, which can include up to 12 ''Freedom''-class ships; the Saudis have not looked to purchase Austal's ''Independence''-class ship. The Saudis, as well as other potential foreign buyers, want permanent weapons capabilities built into the ship rather than interchangeable mission packages. Another potential ship under evaluation was the {{sclass-|Arleigh Burke|destroyer}}; the ''Freedom'' class would be outfitted with vertical missile launchers and the [[SPY-1|SPY-1F radar]], a smaller and lighter but shorter range version of ''Arleigh Burke''{{'}}s SPY-1D. A decision between the ships would be based on the desire for a large-hulled ship with a large missile defense system or a larger number of small-hulled multi-mission ships.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bangordailynews.com/2013/11/21/business/biw-could-get-20-billion-contract-as-saudi-arabia-looks-to-expand-navy/ |title=BIW could get $20 billion contract as Saudi Arabia looks to expand Navy |last=Shalal-Esa |first=Andrea |work=Bangor Daily News |date=21 November 2013 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106065633/http://bangordailynews.com/2013/11/21/business/biw-could-get-20-billion-contract-as-saudi-arabia-looks-to-expand-navy/ |archive-date=6 November 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Saudi Arabia requested the sale of four ''Freedom''-class ships to update its eastern fleet in a potential $11.25 billion deal. The Multi-Mission Surface Combatant (MMSC) variant does away with the LCS modular mission package ability and the forward two mission bays, but keeps the aft mission bay with a stern ramp. The requirement for an Aegis combat system was dropped for cost reasons and the ships will instead feature the TRS-4D AESA air search radar.  Unlike the Flight 0 ''Freedom'', the MMSC features two 8-cell [[Mk 41 VLS]] that can carry 16 SM-2 or 64 ESSMs in total, as well as an [[OTO Melara 76 mm]] main gun, [[RGM-84|Harpoon Block II anti-ship missiles]], torpedoes, and the [[SeaRAM]]. It will also have an [[MH-60R]] helicopter, ASW sonar suites, and the [[Link 16]] data-link for interoperability with regional U.S. forces.<ref name=\"USNI 11.25B Deal\"/><ref name=\"DN 11.25B Deal\" /><ref>[http://www.defensenews.com/story/breaking-news/2015/09/15/saudi-arabia-eastern-fleet-naval-expansion-lockheed-martin-littoral-combat-ship-lcs-us-navy-foreign-military-sales/72303394/ Saudis Said To Zero In on Lockheed LCS] \u2013 Defensenews.com, 15 September 2015</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gowind-class corvette]]\n* [[Independence-class littoral combat ship|''Independence''-class littoral combat ship]]\n* [[Kamorta-class corvette|''Kamorta''-class corvette]]\n* [[Project 20386 corvette|Project 20386]]\n* [[La Fayette-class frigate|''La Fayette''\u2013class frigate]]\n* [[Type 054A frigate]]\n* [[Braunschweig-class corvette]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=72 ''Freedom''-class Littoral Combat Ship on navyrecognition.com]\n{{Marinette Marine|state=autocollapse}} \n{{Littoral combat ships}}\n\n[[Category:Freedom-class littoral combat ships| ]]\n[[Category:Active naval ships of the United States]]\n[[Category:2000s ships]]\n[[Category:2010s ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Marinette Marine]]\n", "name_user": "76.170.74.3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDesign:Added context.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freedom-class_littoral_combat_ship"}
{"title_page": "Jean-Pierre Dubois", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Jean-Pierre Dubois\n| image        =LDH-Dubois-Coupe.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| smallimage   =\n| caption      =Jean-Pierre Dubois (on the right)\n| order        =\n| office1      = Member of League of Human Rights - France\n| term_start1  = \n| predecessor1 =  \n| successor1   =\n| term_start2  = \n| term_end2    = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2   = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=y|1952|05|15}}\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = [[France|French]]\n| party        = \n| spouse       = [[Marie-Christine Vergiat ]]\n| relations    =\n| children     = \n| residence    = \n| alma_mater   =\n| occupation   = Lawyer\n| profession   = Human right activist <br> Politician\n| religion     = \n| website      =\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Jean-Pierre Dubois''' (born May 15, 1952) is a [[France|French]] lawyer and leftist activist. He was president of the  [[Human Rights League (France)]] (LDH) (June 2005 - June 2011). He has been Honorary President of the league since June 2011. <ref>Since its 86th national congress in June 2011.</ref>.\n\n== Career ==\nHe has been professor of public law at the [[University of Paris]] XI since September 1999.\n\nHe joined the [[Saint-Denis, Seine-Saint-Denis|Saint-Denis]] office of LDH in 1986, where he still continues.\n\nIn 2005, he began his 4th term in the central committee of the LDH and his 8th term as a member of the national office where he was previously vice president. Since March 2001, he has been deputy secretary general of the [[International Federation for Human Rights]] (FIDH).  In June, he was elected president of the LDH.<ref>http://www.liberation.fr/societe/2005/06/06/jean-pierre-dubois-elu-president-de-la-ldh_522418</ref>\n\nHis subjects of interest are [[secularism]] and [[globalization]]. He was, on various occasions, assigned to these subjects by the LDH or FIDH and participated in several global and [[Europe]]an social forums, in particular in [[Nicosia]].\nHe married [[Marie-Christine Vergiat]]. They have a daughter, named Fraise.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Human Rights League (France)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dubois, Jean-Pierre}}\n[[Category:French human rights activists]]\n[[Category:French pacifists]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Jean-Pierre Dubois\n| image        =LDH-Dubois-Coupe.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| smallimage   =\n| caption      =Jean-Pierre Dubois (on the right)\n| order        =\n| office1      = Member of League of Human righs - France\n| term_start1  = \n| predecessor1 =  \n| successor1   =\n| term_start2  = \n| term_end2    = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2   = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=y|1952|05|15}}\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = [[France|French]]\n| party        = \n| spouse       = [[Marie-Christine Vergiat ]]\n| relations    =\n| children     = \n| residence    = \n| alma_mater   =\n| occupation   = Lawyer\n| profession   = Human right activist <br> Politician\n| religion     = \n| website      =\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Jean-Pierre Dubois''' (born May 15, 1952) is a [[France|French]] lawyer and leftist activist. He was president of the  [[Human Rights League (France)]] (LDH) (June 2005 - June 2011). He has been Honorary President of the league since June 2011. <ref>Since its 86th national congress in June 2011.</ref>.\n\n== Career ==\nHe has been professor of public law at the [[University of Paris]] XI since September 1999.\n\nHe joined the [[Saint-Denis, Seine-Saint-Denis|Saint-Denis]] office of LDH in 1986, where he still continues.\n\nIn 2005, he began his 4th term in the central committee of the LDH and his 8th term as a member of the national office where he was previously vice president. Since March 2001, he has been deputy secretary general of the [[International Federation for Human Rights]] (FIDH).  In June, he was elected president of the LDH.<ref>http://www.liberation.fr/societe/2005/06/06/jean-pierre-dubois-elu-president-de-la-ldh_522418</ref>\n\nHis subjects of interest are [[secularism]] and [[globalization]]. He was, on various occasions, assigned to these subjects by the LDH or FIDH and participated in several global and [[Europe]]an social forums, in particular in [[Nicosia]].\nHe married [[Marie-Christine Vergiat]]. They have a daughter, named Fraise.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Human Rights League (France)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dubois, Jean-Pierre}}\n[[Category:French human rights activists]]\n[[Category:French pacifists]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Pierre_Dubois"}
{"title_page": "Yashpaul", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Yashpaul\n|image             = Pt_Yashpaul.jpg\n|background      =  solo_singer\n|birth_name      =\n|birth_date            = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1937|03|22}}\n|death_date            =\n|birth_place          = [[Gujranwala]], [[Punjab (British India)|Punjab]], [[British India]]\n|citizenship     = [[File:Flag of India.svg|20px]] [[India]]\n\n|genre           = [[Hindustani classical music]]\n|occupation      = [[Vocalist]]\n|years_active    = 1948\u2013present\n}}\n\nPandit '''Yashpaul''' (born 22 March 1937) is an [[Hindustani classical music|Indian classical]] singer belonging to the [[Agra gharana]] (singing style).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wade|first=Bonnie|date=1973|title=Ch\u0129z in Khy\u0101l: The Traditional Composition in the Improvised Performance|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/849960|journal=Ethnomusicology|volume=17|issue=3|pages=443\u2013459|doi=10.2307/849960|issn=0014-1836}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Wade|first=Bonnie C.|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=MiE9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA102&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Khyal: Creativity Within North India's Classical Music Tradition|date=1984|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-25659-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nYashpaul was born in [[Gujranwala]] in 1937. After the partition his parents migrated to India and settled in [[Jalandhar]], where he was initiated into music by Kasturilal \u2018Jassra\u2019, who was the disciple of Chhote Ghulam Ali Khan of Lahore.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.amritkirtan.com/pt-yashpaul.html :: Felicitation of Pt. Yashpaul Ji ::<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationalnewsandviews.com/festival-of-performing-arts-begins-akademi-awardees-showcase-their-art/|title=Festival of Performing Arts begins, Akademi Awardees showcase their Art|website=www.internationalnewsandviews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> He received further training from [[Vilayat Hussain Khan]] and [[Yunus Hussain Khan]] from the [[Agra gharana]]. He was also inspired by Bade Ghulam Ali Khan and Mallikarjun Mansur.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Sinha|first=Manjari|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/the-taste-of-organic-fruit/article24998033.ece|title=The taste of \u2018organic\u2019 fruit: Pandit Yashpaul and the Agra gharana|date=21 September 2018|work=The Hindu|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anadfoundation.org/guru-gaurav-350/performers/ransubai/pandit-yashpaul/|title=Pandit Yashpaul|date=2017-03-23|website=The An\u0101d Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20031115/windows/main1.htm|title=A fine music tradition in ruins|date=15 November 2003|work=The Tribune|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nYashpaul first performed when he was 11 years old at the \"Harivallabh Sangeet Sammelan\".<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He is the oldest alumni of Swami Harballabh Sangeet Akademi, Jalandhar. He has been performing on [[All India Radio]] since 1952. He has performed in many nationally-broadcast programmes of music, as well as annual Akashvani Sangeet Sammelans.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030814/cth2.htm | title=At last, recognition to guardian of Agra Gharana | date=13 August 2003 | newspaper=The Tribune | location=Chandigarh, India | first=Aditi | last=Tandon | accessdate=8 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nHe is a composer and teacher. He has composed many ''[[bandish]]es'' under his [[nom de plume]] \"Sagun Piya\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/exploring-gandhi-through-bharatnatyam-mudras/1016535/|title=Exploring Gandhi through mudras|date=14 October 2012|work=The Indian Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He retired as the Head of Department at the Department Music at [[Panjab University]] in 1997.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Department-of-Music-Vocal-of-PG-Government-College-for-Girls-Sector-11-Chandigarh-organized-a-Lecture-cum-Demonstration-today-Pt-Yash-Paul-an-eminent-and-traditional-performing-artist-who-has-made-a-significant-contribution-in-the-field-of-Hindustani-Classical-Vocal-Music-was-the-resource-person-/articleshow/7515550.cms|title=Department of Music (Vocal) of PG Government College for Girls, Sector-11, Chandigarh organized a Lecture-cum-Demonstration today. Pt. Yash Paul, an eminent and traditional performing artist, who has made a significant contribution in the field of Hindustani Classical Vocal Music, was the resource-person. - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nAwards received by Yashpaul include:.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianschoolofmusic.com/2015/09/28/pandit-yashpaul/|title=Pandit Yashpaul - Asian School of Music|last=|first=|date=28 September 2015|website=Asian School of Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n \n*National Sangeet Natak Academy Award\n*Award of National Scholarship, 1962 (Ministry of Education, Govt. of India)\n*Punjab State award\n*Punjab Sangeet Natak Academi award\n*Dedicated Educationist award\n*Sangeet Sumeru award\n*Sangeet Shiromani award\n*The Music Monarch of India\u2019s north western region (the lifetime award by FFF)\n*Honored by Senior Citizens Association of Chandigarh\n*He is the founder and former Chairman of Deptts. of Music i.e., M.C.M. D.A.V. College for Women and Punjab University Chandigarh respectively\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yashpaul}}\n[[Category:People from Gujranwala]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Agra gharana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{non-notable|date=April 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Yashpaul\n|image             = Pt_Yashpaul.jpg\n|background      =  solo_singer\n|birth_name      =\n|birth_date            = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1937|03|22}}\n|death_date            =\n|birth_place          = [[Gujranwala]], [[Punjab (British India)|Punjab]], [[British India]]\n|citizenship     = [[File:Flag of India.svg|20px]] [[India]]\n\n|genre           = [[Hindustani classical music]]\n|occupation      = [[Vocalist]]\n|years_active    = 1948\u2013present\n}}\n\nPandit '''Yashpaul''' (born 22 March 1937) is an [[Hindustani classical music|Indian classical]] singer belonging to the [[Agra gharana]] (singing style).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wade|first=Bonnie|date=1973|title=Ch\u0129z in Khy\u0101l: The Traditional Composition in the Improvised Performance|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/849960|journal=Ethnomusicology|volume=17|issue=3|pages=443\u2013459|doi=10.2307/849960|issn=0014-1836}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Wade|first=Bonnie C.|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=MiE9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA102&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Khyal: Creativity Within North India's Classical Music Tradition|date=1984|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-25659-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nYashpaul was born in [[Gujranwala]] in 1937. After the partition his parents migrated to India and settled in [[Jalandhar]], where he was initiated into music by Kasturilal \u2018Jassra\u2019, who was the disciple of Chhote Ghulam Ali Khan of Lahore.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.amritkirtan.com/pt-yashpaul.html :: Felicitation of Pt. Yashpaul Ji ::<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationalnewsandviews.com/festival-of-performing-arts-begins-akademi-awardees-showcase-their-art/|title=Festival of Performing Arts begins, Akademi Awardees showcase their Art|website=www.internationalnewsandviews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> He received further training from [[Vilayat Hussain Khan]] and [[Yunus Hussain Khan]] from the [[Agra gharana]]. He was also inspired by Bade Ghulam Ali Khan and Mallikarjun Mansur.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Sinha|first=Manjari|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/the-taste-of-organic-fruit/article24998033.ece|title=The taste of \u2018organic\u2019 fruit: Pandit Yashpaul and the Agra gharana|date=21 September 2018|work=The Hindu|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anadfoundation.org/guru-gaurav-350/performers/ransubai/pandit-yashpaul/|title=Pandit Yashpaul|date=2017-03-23|website=The An\u0101d Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20031115/windows/main1.htm|title=A fine music tradition in ruins|date=15 November 2003|work=The Tribune|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nYashpaul first performed when he was 11 years old at the \"Harivallabh Sangeet Sammelan\".<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He is the oldest alumni of Swami Harballabh Sangeet Akademi, Jalandhar. He has been performing on [[All India Radio]] since 1952. He has performed in many nationally-broadcast programmes of music, as well as annual Akashvani Sangeet Sammelans.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030814/cth2.htm | title=At last, recognition to guardian of Agra Gharana | date=13 August 2003 | newspaper=The Tribune | location=Chandigarh, India | first=Aditi | last=Tandon | accessdate=8 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nHe is a composer and teacher. He has composed many ''[[bandish]]es'' under his [[nom de plume]] \"Sagun Piya\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/exploring-gandhi-through-bharatnatyam-mudras/1016535/|title=Exploring Gandhi through mudras|date=14 October 2012|work=The Indian Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He retired as the Head of Department at the Department Music at [[Panjab University]] in 1997.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Department-of-Music-Vocal-of-PG-Government-College-for-Girls-Sector-11-Chandigarh-organized-a-Lecture-cum-Demonstration-today-Pt-Yash-Paul-an-eminent-and-traditional-performing-artist-who-has-made-a-significant-contribution-in-the-field-of-Hindustani-Classical-Vocal-Music-was-the-resource-person-/articleshow/7515550.cms|title=Department of Music (Vocal) of PG Government College for Girls, Sector-11, Chandigarh organized a Lecture-cum-Demonstration today. Pt. Yash Paul, an eminent and traditional performing artist, who has made a significant contribution in the field of Hindustani Classical Vocal Music, was the resource-person. - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nAwards received by Yashpaul include:.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asianschoolofmusic.com/2015/09/28/pandit-yashpaul/|title=Pandit Yashpaul - Asian School of Music|last=|first=|date=28 September 2015|website=Asian School of Music|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n \n*National Sangeet Natak Academy Award\n*Award of National Scholarship, 1962 (Ministry of Education, Govt. of India)\n*Punjab State award\n*Punjab Sangeet Natak Academi award\n*Dedicated Educationist award\n*Sangeet Sumeru award\n*Sangeet Shiromani award\n*The Music Monarch of India\u2019s north western region (the lifetime award by FFF)\n*Honored by Senior Citizens Association of Chandigarh\n*He is the founder and former Chairman of Deptts. of Music i.e., M.C.M. D.A.V. College for Women and Punjab University Chandigarh respectively\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yashpaul}}\n[[Category:People from Gujranwala]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[