{"title_page": "Hasteda Jain Mandir", "text_new": "{{short description|Temple in Jaipur, India; the most sacred site}}\n{{other uses|Jain Temple (disambiguation)| (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name           = Hasteda Jain Mandir\n| native_name    = \n| native_name_lang = pa\n| image          = [[File:28 march.jpg|thumb|]]\n| image_size     = 500\n| caption        = Hasteda Jain Mandir\n| religious_affiliation= [[Jainism]]\n| location       = [[Jaipur]]\n| state          = [[Jaipur, India|Rajasthan]]\n| country        = India\n| map_type       = India #India#Asia\n| map_size       = 200\n\n| year_completed = 9th Feb 2019 \n\n| website = [http://prabhusar.org/shri-digambar-jain-mandir/ Prabhusar Official Website]\n}}\n'''ATIPRACHIN MANOROTHPURN SHRI'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=shorturl.at/aqyAX|title=Atiprachin|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>1008 MUNISUVARTNATH ATISHAY KSHETRA, popularly known as Hasteda Jain Mandir is the one of the oldest Jain Mandir in Jaipur District, Rajasthan located in the village of Hasteda, situated 24 kms away from Chomu town..\n\n==BACKGROUND OF THE TEMPLE==\nHasteda Jain Mandir was known to only a few Jain followers until April 2018. There were over 100 Jain families residing there till the year 1950 but over a period of time most of the families migrated to different parts of India. The temple was neglected for a long time, which led it in extremely precarious & pathetic conditions.\n\n==SHRI 1008 MUNISUVRATNATH JAIN MANDIR==\nHasteda along with Paithan and Jahazpur is known for their ancient idols of Lord Munisuvratnath. The temple at Hasteda, Paithan and jahazpur is dedicated to Munisuvrata the twentieth Tirthankara of Jainism. Idol at Hasteda is the 2nd oldest Idol of Lord Munisuvratnath.   \n\n==MUNISUVRATNATH==\nAccording to Jain texts, munisuvratanatha was born as 34 lakh plus 25,000 years passed after the birth of the nineteenth tirthankara, Mallinatha. According to Jain beliefs, Munisuvratnatha descended from the heaven called \u0100nata kalpa on the twelfth day of the bright half of the month of \u0100\u015bvina \u2013 \u0101\u015bvina \u015bukla dv\u0101da\u015bi\u2013 to Queen Padm\u0101 and King Sumitra.\n\nIn his previous incarnation, Munisuvrata was born as Surshreshta, the king of Champa, Mahavideh. On the third day of Shraavana (month) Krishna (dark fortnight) according to Hindu calendar, Queen Padmavati of Rajgir saw sixteen auspicious dreams. When she shared her dreams with her husband, King Sumitra of the Harivamsa clan, he explained that a Tirthankara will be born to them soon. Then, Munisuvrata was born to them on the fifteenth day of the Shraavana Shukla (bright fortnight) in 1,184,980 BC.\n\nAccording to Jain texts, after spending 7,500 years as youth (kumarakala), Munisuvratan\u0101tha ruled His kingdom for 15,000 years (r\u0101jyak\u0101la). He then renounced all worldly pursuits and became a monk. According to Jain beliefs, Munisuvratan\u0101tha spent 11 months (chadmasthak\u0101la) performing karma-destroying austerities and then attained the all-embracing knowledge \u2013 Omniscience (kevala j\u00f1\u0101na).\n\n==RESTORATION JOURNEY OF THE HASTEDA JAIN MANDIR ==\nThe ancient tenets of the temple traced its lineage and its significance. The research unveiled startling facts about the temple and the various idols present at the temple. Which clarified that this temple has one of the largest collection of ancient Jain idols located at a single place.\n\nThe progress took a major leap with the involvement of experts in the field of vastu, archaeology and residents of the village. The news of its ancientness soon spread like wild fire among all migrants of the village who had settled elsewhere in the country and began flocking to the temple for Darshan. Migrants were so overwhelmed with the restoration (Jirnodhar) that some people donated their residential building, gold, cash, etc. for this holy cause.\n\n==ABOUT HASTEDA VILLAGE==\n\nHasteda village is situated in Teshil Chomu, District Jaipur and in State of Rajasthan, India. The Village has population of 4489 as per census data of year 2011, in which male population was 2304 and female population was 2185. Total geographical area of Hasteda village is 1225.01 Hectares and the Population density of Hasteda is 4 people per Hectares. Total number of houses hold in the village is 757 and there are average of 6 people live in every family.\n\nIt is the most populated villages among many other villages situated at Chomu, sub district of Jaipur, Rajasthan. Total geographical area of Hasteda village is 12 km and it is the 12th biggest village by area in the sub district. The nearest town of Hasteda village is Chomu and the distance from the village to Chomu is around 24 km.\n\nHasteda village has its own post office and the pin code of Hasteda village is 303712. Out of the total village area, 4.03 km (33%) of the village area is covered with greenery.\n66% of the population of the village are of general caste and 26% are from schedule caste and 8% are schedule tribes.\n\n==FACTS==\n\nIn this journey of restoration, it was found that the pratima (idol) of SRI MUNISUVARTNATH, 20th Jain tirthankar is dated back to vikram samwat 1209 (1152 AD) and the breath of life (pratishtha) was solemnized by Acharya Sriyut Swamy Ji Mahraj, in the presence of his 13 followers sadhus. It is to be noted that, prior to this, there is no proven evidence of the presence of a Digambar Jain Acharya prior to Mughal period that too for solemnizing the breath of life (pratishtha) to the idol and the same is duly engraved in the idol of Sri Munisuvartnath.\n\nThere are 15 other Jain idols, which all stated to be older than 350 years old. During the course of restoration work, two shilalekhs were traced in one of the temple walls. Now these engraved scripture are well preserved. As per the readings of the Shilalekhs, the evidence of one of the Jirnodhar or redesigning traced back to 1704 AD.\n\nThe Moolnayak Idol of Sri Munisuvratnath is stated to be the 2nd most ancient idol of Lord Munisuvratnath. As per Jain\u2019s beliefs Lord Sri Munisuvratnath is the influencer of Saturn planet and it is believed that anyone suffering from curse of planet Saturn or anyone wishes to enhance the power of Saturn as per his zodiac chart, gets relief by visiting the temple and chanting mantra as prescribed in Jain scriptures (jinvani).\n\n==LEGEND==\n\nWhen one of the migrants visited the village and passed by the temple, a very old man appeared and said that the people in the village in the ancient times used to chant \u201cDeen Ke Dayal Ji Kar Do Nihal Ji\u201d. This old man never appeared again nor was seen subsequently by anybody.\n\nThe second legend is prior to restoration work. There were thousands of bats that were hovering above the Mool Bedi. All the bats instantly disappeared itself after the vow (sanklap) of restoration pledged by several jain believers on 10th April 2018.\n\n== REFERENCE ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Temple in Jaipur, India; the most sacred site}}\n{{other uses|Jain Temple (disambiguation)| (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name           = Hasteda Jain Mandir\n| native_name    = \n| native_name_lang = pa\n| image          = [[File:28 march.jpg|thumb|]]\n| image_size     = 500\n| caption        = Hasteda Jain Mandir\n| religious_affiliation= [[Jainism]]\n| location       = [[Jaipur]]\n| state          = [[Jaipur, India|Rajasthan]]\n| country        = India\n| map_type       = India #India#Asia\n| map_size       = 200\n\n| year_completed = 9th Feb 2019 \n\n| website = [http://prabhusar.org/shri-digambar-jain-mandir/ Prabhusar Official Website]\n}}\n'''ATIPRACHIN MANOROTHPURN'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=shorturl.at/aqyAX|title=Atiprachin|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>1008 MUNISUVARTNATH ATISHAY KSHETRA, popularly known as Hasteda Jain Mandir is the one of the oldest Jain Mandir in Jaipur District, Rajasthan located in the village of Hasteda, situated 24 kms away from Chomu town..\n\n==BACKGROUND OF THE TEMPLE==\nHasteda Jain Mandir was known to only a few Jain followers until April 2018. There were over 100 Jain families residing there till the year 1950 but over a period of time most of the families migrated to different parts of India. The temple was neglected for a long time, which led it in extremely precarious & pathetic conditions.\n\n==SHRI 1008 MUNISUVRATNATH JAIN MANDIR==\nHasteda along with Paithan and Jahazpur is known for their ancient idols of Lord Munisuvratnath. The temple at Hasteda, Paithan and jahazpur is dedicated to Munisuvrata the twentieth Tirthankara of Jainism. Idol at Hasteda is the 2nd oldest Idol of Lord Munisuvratnath.   \n\n==MUNISUVRATNATH==\nAccording to Jain texts, munisuvratanatha was born as 34 lakh plus 25,000 years passed after the birth of the nineteenth tirthankara, Mallinatha. According to Jain beliefs, Munisuvratnatha descended from the heaven called \u0100nata kalpa on the twelfth day of the bright half of the month of \u0100\u015bvina \u2013 \u0101\u015bvina \u015bukla dv\u0101da\u015bi\u2013 to Queen Padm\u0101 and King Sumitra.\n\nIn his previous incarnation, Munisuvrata was born as Surshreshta, the king of Champa, Mahavideh. On the third day of Shraavana (month) Krishna (dark fortnight) according to Hindu calendar, Queen Padmavati of Rajgir saw sixteen auspicious dreams. When she shared her dreams with her husband, King Sumitra of the Harivamsa clan, he explained that a Tirthankara will be born to them soon. Then, Munisuvrata was born to them on the fifteenth day of the Shraavana Shukla (bright fortnight) in 1,184,980 BC.\n\nAccording to Jain texts, after spending 7,500 years as youth (kumarakala), Munisuvratan\u0101tha ruled His kingdom for 15,000 years (r\u0101jyak\u0101la). He then renounced all worldly pursuits and became a monk. According to Jain beliefs, Munisuvratan\u0101tha spent 11 months (chadmasthak\u0101la) performing karma-destroying austerities and then attained the all-embracing knowledge \u2013 Omniscience (kevala j\u00f1\u0101na).\n\n==RESTORATION JOURNEY OF THE HASTEDA JAIN MANDIR ==\nThe ancient tenets of the temple traced its lineage and its significance. The research unveiled startling facts about the temple and the various idols present at the temple. Which clarified that this temple has one of the largest collection of ancient Jain idols located at a single place.\n\nThe progress took a major leap with the involvement of experts in the field of vastu, archaeology and residents of the village. The news of its ancientness soon spread like wild fire among all migrants of the village who had settled elsewhere in the country and began flocking to the temple for Darshan. Migrants were so overwhelmed with the restoration (Jirnodhar) that some people donated their residential building, gold, cash, etc. for this holy cause.\n\n==ABOUT HASTEDA VILLAGE==\n\nHasteda village is situated in Teshil Chomu, District Jaipur and in State of Rajasthan, India. The Village has population of 4489 as per census data of year 2011, in which male population was 2304 and female population was 2185. Total geographical area of Hasteda village is 1225.01 Hectares and the Population density of Hasteda is 4 people per Hectares. Total number of houses hold in the village is 757 and there are average of 6 people live in every family.\n\nIt is the most populated villages among many other villages situated at Chomu, sub district of Jaipur, Rajasthan. Total geographical area of Hasteda village is 12 km and it is the 12th biggest village by area in the sub district. The nearest town of Hasteda village is Chomu and the distance from the village to Chomu is around 24 km.\n\nHasteda village has its own post office and the pin code of Hasteda village is 303712. Out of the total village area, 4.03 km (33%) of the village area is covered with greenery.\n66% of the population of the village are of general caste and 26% are from schedule caste and 8% are schedule tribes.\n\n==FACTS==\n\nIn this journey of restoration, it was found that the pratima (idol) of SRI MUNISUVARTNATH, 20th Jain tirthankar is dated back to vikram samwat 1209 (1152 AD) and the breath of life (pratishtha) was solemnized by Acharya Sriyut Swamy Ji Mahraj, in the presence of his 13 followers sadhus. It is to be noted that, prior to this, there is no proven evidence of the presence of a Digambar Jain Acharya prior to Mughal period that too for solemnizing the breath of life (pratishtha) to the idol and the same is duly engraved in the idol of Sri Munisuvartnath.\n\nThere are 15 other Jain idols, which all stated to be older than 350 years old. During the course of restoration work, two shilalekhs were traced in one of the temple walls. Now these engraved scripture are well preserved. As per the readings of the Shilalekhs, the evidence of one of the Jirnodhar or redesigning traced back to 1704 AD.\n\nThe Moolnayak Idol of Sri Munisuvratnath is stated to be the 2nd most ancient idol of Lord Munisuvratnath. As per Jain\u2019s beliefs Lord Sri Munisuvratnath is the influencer of Saturn planet and it is believed that anyone suffering from curse of planet Saturn or anyone wishes to enhance the power of Saturn as per his zodiac chart, gets relief by visiting the temple and chanting mantra as prescribed in Jain scriptures (jinvani).\n\n==LEGEND==\n\nWhen one of the migrants visited the village and passed by the temple, a very old man appeared and said that the people in the village in the ancient times used to chant \u201cDeen Ke Dayal Ji Kar Do Nihal Ji\u201d. This old man never appeared again nor was seen subsequently by anybody.\n\nThe second legend is prior to restoration work. There were thousands of bats that were hovering above the Mool Bedi. All the bats instantly disappeared itself after the vow (sanklap) of restoration pledged by several jain believers on 10th April 2018.\n\n== REFERENCE ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Devkumar20201", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hasteda_Jain_Mandir"}
